            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I'm not sure that it's possible to get all that close with `nvim_parse_cmd`. Yes, I could use that to rewrite my own commands by looking for commands like /, ?, :s[ubstitute], :g[lobal], :filt[er], :helpg[rep], :fu[nction], and :vim[grep]. I think that's an exhaustive list of things that match on {pattern} - that's a lot of commands to rewrite. Abbreviations also wouldn't cover things like \":fu /\" without broadening them quite a bit.\n\nBut if I want to *also* change the behavior of patterns including those passed to plugin commands, that's another step up in complexity. I want all my patterns to use good syntax without having to put extra effort into each place they're used or think about what route it's going to take.\n\nIdeally, I think very-magic mode would be the default. The only modes that make sense to me are very-no-magic and very-magic. The in-between options are just adding extra typing and thinking - do I need a backslash for this regex operator? What about this one? [neo]vim even has a couple extra weird ones like ~, which I've never seen used like that in any other text processing language.",
